Abstract = {The decentralized nature of the Bitcoin blockchain is a cornerstone of
   its success, yet measuring true decentralization remains a significant
   challenge. Moreover, with the institutional participants entering the
   space, there is an increasing necessity for compliance with global
   financial regulations, to perform forensic analysis for fraud-activity,
   etc., and yet, ensuring the integrity of a transaction with high
   probability of it being validated in a truly decentralized way is not as
   straight forward as the media and industry reports communicate. Our
   approach consists of two key components. First, we present an
   open-source Extract, Transform, Load (ETL) process tailored for
   blockchain data, which fosters improved analytical transparency and aids
   regulatory and forensic analysis. Secondly, we apply a graph-based
   Bitcoin addresses. This method is chosen for its robustness in handling
   relational data and its ability to focus selectively on informative
   parts of the transaction through controlled experiments, yielding: 10
   years of driving innovation in the field.},
