   09-11, 2017},
Abstract = {Personal names found on drives provide forensically valuable information
   about users of systems. This work reports on the design and engineering
   of tools to mine them from disk images, bootstrapping on output of the
   Bulk Extractor tool. However, most potential names found are either
   uninteresting sales and help contacts or are not being used as names, so
   we developed methods to rate name-candidate value by an analysis of the
   clues that they and their context provide. We used an empirically based
   approach with statistics from a large corpus from which we extracted 303
   million email addresses and 74 million phone numbers, and then found 302
   million personal names. We tested three machine-learning approaches and
   Naive Bayes performed the best. Cross-modal clues from nearby email
   addresses improved performance still further. This approach eliminated
   from consideration 71.3\% of the addresses found in our corpus with an
   estimated 67.4\% F-score, a potential 3.5 times reduction in the name
   workload of most forensic investigations.},
